---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

export const meta = {
  title: 'Best Fonts Guide: Typeface Selection for Web, Logos & Resumes',
  description: 'Font selection guide covering the best fonts for resumes, web, logos, and coding. Includes serif vs sans-serif comparison, pairing rules, and Google Fonts.',
  category: 'list',
  published: '2026-03-24'
};

const SITE_ID = 'papyruspeople';

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article"
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the difference between serif and sans-serif fonts?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Serif fonts have small decorative strokes (serifs) at the ends of characters and are traditionally considered more formal and legible in print. Sans-serif fonts lack these strokes, offering a cleaner, more modern look that is highly readable on digital screens."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the best fonts for a resume?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For a resume, you want fonts that are professional and easy to read. Excellent choices include classic serif fonts like Garamond or modern sans-serifs like Calibri, Helvetica, and Arial."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What makes a good font for coding?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Good coding fonts are typically monospaced (each character takes up the same horizontal space), have distinct characters for easily confused symbols (like '1', 'I', 'l'), and often include programming ligatures. Top choices include JetBrains Mono, Fira Code, and Cascadia Code."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are variable fonts?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Variable fonts are a single font file that acts like multiple fonts. They allow you to dynamically adjust characteristics like weight, width, and slant, offering endless typographical flexibility while reducing web page load times."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does OFL mean in font licensing?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "OFL stands for SIL Open Font License. It is a free and open-source license that allows fonts to be used freely, modified, and redistributed, making it ideal for both personal and commercial web projects without licensing fees."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---

<SiteLayout
  site={SITE_ID}
  title={meta.title}
  description={meta.description}
  schema={JSON.stringify(schema)}
  canonical="https://papyruspeople.photonbuilder.com/best-fonts-guide"
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Best Fonts Guide</h1>
      <p>Discover the perfect typeface for any project. Compare serif, sans-serif, monospace, and display fonts. Find the best fonts for web, logos, resumes, coding, and more.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Font Types Explained: Serif vs Sans-Serif vs Monospace vs Display</h2>
      <p>Understanding the basic font classifications is crucial for making the right choice:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Serif:</strong> Characterized by small lines at the ends of strokes (e.g., Times New Roman). Great for long printed documents and conveying authority or tradition.</li>
        <li><strong>Sans-Serif:</strong> Without serifs (e.g., Helvetica). Modern, clean, and highly readable on screens.</li>
        <li><strong>Monospace:</strong> Every character takes up the exact same width (e.g., Courier). Essential for coding and tabular data alignment.</li>
        <li><strong>Display:</strong> Highly decorative fonts meant for large headings and logos, not for body text.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Best Fonts by Use Case</h2>

      <h3>Best Fonts for Resumes</h3>
      <p>Your resume needs to be professional and legible at small sizes. <strong>Garamond</strong> is a timeless, elegant serif choice that saves space. For a more contemporary feel, <strong>Calibri</strong> is an excellent, widely available sans-serif option that looks clean on screens and print.</p>

      <h3>Best Fonts for Web</h3>
      <p>Web fonts must prioritize legibility on various devices and resolutions. <strong>Inter</strong>, <strong>Roboto</strong>, and <strong>Open Sans</strong> are among the best choices. They are highly legible, offer extensive character sets, and are optimized for UI design and body text.</p>

      <h3>Best Fonts for Logos</h3>
      <p>Logos require distinctive typography that aligns with brand identity. Display fonts or highly customized sans-serifs are often used. The best font depends entirely on the brand's personality—whether it's playful, luxurious, tech-focused, or traditional.</p>

      <h3>Best Coding Fonts</h3>
      <p>Developers spend hours looking at code, making legible monospace fonts crucial. Top choices with programming ligatures (combining symbols like '!=' into a single glyph) include <strong>JetBrains Mono</strong>, <strong>Fira Code</strong>, and <strong>Cascadia Code</strong>.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Font Pairing Rules & Best Practices</h2>
      <p>Combining fonts effectively is an art. Here are key rules:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Contrast is Key:</strong> Pair a bold sans-serif heading with a readable serif body text, or vice versa. Avoid pairing two fonts that look very similar.</li>
        <li><strong>Limit Your Selection:</strong> Stick to two, or at most three, font families per project to maintain visual harmony.</li>
        <li><strong>Use Superfamilies:</strong> Some fonts come with both serif and sans-serif variations (e.g., Roboto and Roboto Slab). These pair together perfectly.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Technical Considerations: Variable Fonts, Licensing & Accessibility</h2>

      <h3>Google Fonts Top 20 & Variable Fonts</h3>
      <p>Google Fonts offers a massive library of free web fonts. Many of the top 20, like Roboto and Inter, are now available as <strong>Variable Fonts</strong>. Instead of loading separate files for bold, italic, and regular, a variable font encapsulates all styles in one file, improving website performance and typographic flexibility.</p>

      <h3>Font Licensing: OFL vs Commercial</h3>
      <p>Always check a font's license before use. <strong>OFL (SIL Open Font License)</strong> allows for free commercial and personal use. Commercial fonts, found on foundries or sites like MyFonts, require purchasing a license specific to your use case (desktop, web, app).</p>

      <h3>Readability and Accessibility</h3>
      <p>Accessibility should be a priority. Choose fonts with clear distinctions between easily confused letters (like 'I', 'l', and '1'). For readers with dyslexia, specific dyslexia-friendly fonts exist, though widely spaced, clean sans-serifs like Arial and Comic Sans also tend to perform better for dyslexic users.</p>

      <h3>Where to Find Free Fonts</h3>
      <p>Reliable sources for high-quality, free fonts include Google Fonts, Font Squirrel (which heavily curates for commercial-use-friendly licenses), and the open-source community on GitHub.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      {schema[1].mainEntity.map((faq: any) => (
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>{faq.name}</h3>
          <p>{faq.acceptedAnswer.text}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

  <style>
    .page-content { max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; margin-bottom: 2.5rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.5rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }

    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color, #2a2418); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; }

    .content-section { margin-top: 2rem; }
    .content-section h2 { font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .content-section h3 { font-size: 1.15rem; font-weight: 600; margin-top: 1.25rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .content-section p { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
    ul { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
    li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }

    .faq-item { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color, #2a2418); padding-bottom: 1.25rem; margin-bottom: 1.25rem; }
    .faq-item:last-child { border-bottom: none; margin-bottom: 0; padding-bottom: 0; }
    .faq-item h3 { margin-top: 0; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
